A meal I used to make Matthew and I in college is now a meal I make for our family of five. We love a simple, easy recipe for those busy school nights. Save this for the next time you need a quick and yummy meal your whole family will love. @ragu #ad #ragu
 
1 lb. Mild Italian Sausage 
½ Red Pepper, washed and sliced 
½ Yellow Pepper, washed and sliced 
½ Green Pepper, washed and sliced  
8 oz. Cream Cheese 
1 – 14-oz. Jar RAGÚ® Simply Roasted Garlic Sauce 
8 oz. Penne Pasta, uncooked 
1 Tbsp. Basil leaves, shredded, for garnish 
Salt and pepper to taste
 
Heat medium pot of water to boil, add penne and cook according to package instructions. Then heat up a drizzle of olive oil in a separate large pot and add Italian sausage. Allow the sausage to cook and then add all three peppers to sauté together. Once the peppers are soft, add the entire jar of RAGÚ® and mix. Cut up the cream-cheese block into small cubes and add them to the sauce. Stir until all is melted and combined. Then add salt and pepper to taste. Once the penne is cooked fully, drain the water and add the penne to the sauce pot. Stir and plate. Add basil for garnish and enjoy!

When our kids (or ourselves) fail to achieve milestones at the times we expect, we tend to worry. It’s because we focus so much on the average. 
This got me thinking about all the times I’ve looked to my right and worried that I wasn’t doing what my neighbor was doing. All the times I felt like I wasn’t “meeting the average” because I wasn’t on the same path as the people around me. I kept reminding myself of the path I was designed for. You’re blessed when you stay on your course created by God. It’s about to be summer, we’ve got lots of plans, we’ve got a packed schedule but let me tell you one very important thing to do: put a small toy in the front seat with you. This is all to remind you to check your back seats. In partnership with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration and the Ad Council, I wanted to share with you some facts and reminders. Hot car deaths are the leading cause of non-crash related fatalities for children 14 and under. This is because a child’s body temp rises 3-5 times faster than an adult's body, and the temperature inside your car can increase 20 degrees in just 10 minutes. Never leave your child in a car, even if you’re only gone for a minute. Heatstroke can happen at any time of year and at temperatures as low as 57 degrees. A window cracked does very little to keep the car cool. No one thinks they will forget their child in the car, but it could happen to anyone. Putting your child’s favorite toy next to your purse or keys, prompts you to check your backseat so you never forget them when you leave your car. The summer is coming to a close, and I cannot believe it but both girls learned how to swim. We retired the life jackets, but It’s important to remember that drowning can happen to anyone, regardless of age or swimming ability. Especially because there is an average of 4,012 unintentional drowning deaths per year. Drowning is fast and silent. It can happen in as little as 20-60 seconds. I wanted to share 5 layers of protection for a little reminder. Save this post!

+Barriers & Alarms:
It’s important to use four-sided fencing with self-closing, self-latching gates, pool
safety covers, and alarm systems to help prevent children and unauthorized
adults from accessing water unsupervised.

+Supervision:
Stay vigilant and aware of your surroundings with close, constant, and capable
adult supervision from a designated water watcher or lifeguard anytime children
are in or around water.

+Water Competency:
Every child and adult should be equipped with the skills to protect themselves in
water by learning and enhancing their basic water safety skills to reduce the risk
of drowning and aquatic-related injuries.

+Life Jackets:
When used appropriately, life jackets protect you when you are not expecting
to be in the water, especially around open water. Ensure your life jackets are
tested & approved by the USCG.

+Emergency Preparation:
Knowing how to prepare for an emergency with CPR training with rescue
breaths, and basic water rescue skills can make the difference between life and
death. Have a phone available and ready to call 911

Learn more and stay up to date with @drownalliance

Back in 2020 when Penelope was in the NICU, the doctors had no answers, we had no direction, and all we had was faith. We didn’t want to think about when we were supposed to go back to work, what we were going to eat each day, or how we were going to pay for the loads of expenses that were to come, because all we needed to think about was Penelope. We were transformed by truth and this is why we value @RMHC so much. The charity supports millions of families going through similar situations that we found ourselves in unexpectedly just 3 years ago by supporting them during some of the hardest times they will ever face. RMHC does so much, but some of the relief the organization provides include accommodations near hospitals for the families that must travel far from home to find care and even easing financial burdens for lodging and meal costs.
You can support RMHC by making a financial contribution, supplying donations, volunteering, or even sharing a meal with families like we did earlier this year with the girls at @RMHCCF. We were able to bring in some fun activities and games for the kids as well as some materials to have some fun in the kitchen. The girls made cookies and we got to sit and talk with some of the families there to hear their stories and hopefully spread joy.
We want to encourage you to support RMHC this season of giving. We realized when you find yourself in a situation like this, you will be transformed to increase in your giving whether it’s your talents, money or time. What can you give generously this season to the families who need it most?
